   {
      "author_association" : "MEMBER",
      "body" : "I would guess the only limiting factors are available memory and time. Where the latter one is not strict, as RPC timeouts are client-side and can be adjusted. Systems with a huge wallet likely already have lot of memory to support that in the first place.\r\n\r\nThe only time I really had to look into HTTP streaming (so delivering the data as it was generated without accumulating it into a buffer) was for making it possible to download the UTXO set (#7759). But this turned out to be impossible to do reliably with our execution model and libevent's single-threaded HTTP server.\r\n\r\n(Something to keep in mind when using a JSON-RPC though, is that most clients are *also* going to waste a lot of memory parsing and storing the entire thing instead of downloading it to disk. This is necessary to get the error/status information that wraps it. For larger data it might be better to use HTTP directly so the result can be downloaded as a file.)\r\n",
      "created_at" : "2021-08-05T10:12:15Z",
      "html_url" : "https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/issues/20866#issuecomment-893337682",
